{"cursor":"1677","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\nIn filmmaking and television production 'presence' (or 'room tone') is the\n\"silence\" recorded at a location or space when no dialogue is spoken. Sound\nfor Digital Video by Tomlinson Holman (Focal Press) 2005 (p. 162-164) This\nterm is often confused with ambience.\n\nEvery location has a distinct presence created by the position of the microphone\nin relation to the space boundaries. A microphone placed in two different\nlocations of the same room will produce two different presences. This is because\nof the unique spatial relationship between the microphone and boundaries such as\nwalls, ceiling, floor and other objects in the\nroom. http://www.linkwitzlab.com/rooms.htm\n\nPresence is recorded during the production stage of filmmaking. It is used to\nhelp create the film sound track, where presence may be intercut with dialogue\nto smooth out any sound edit points. The sound track \"going dead\" would be\nperceived by the audience not as silence, but as a failure of the sound system.\n\nFor this reason presence is normally recorded - like dialogue - in mono, with\nthe microphone in the same position and orientation as the original dialogue\nrecording. Dialogue Editing for Motion Pictures by John Purcell (Focal\nPress) 2007 (p. 148) In the sound edit, presence occupies the same track\nas the dialogue to which it applies.\n","linknr":97,"url":"Presence_(sound_recording)","recorded":1363181614,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Presence_(sound_recording)&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Presence_(sound_recording)&action=edit","//en.wikipedia.org/apple-touch-icon.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinser